{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489869"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:33:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:33:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"766"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/766"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.02,0.07,0.58,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"766"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47773"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/766"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"766"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32495"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1164"},{"type":"tags","id":"2141"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"5980"},{"type":"tags","id":"9347"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3795"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40111"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47773"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man is day five post-open surgical clipping of a ruptured anterior communicating artery aneurysm. He has been generally well since the surgery, alert and oriented with GCS 15 and no focal neurological deficits. He has no significant past medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe nurse calls a MET call for a two-minute generalised tonic-clonic seizure, which has now ended. On review, you find him drowsy, disoriented and complaining of new headache. On examination, there is a left-sided facial droop and 4/5 weakness of the left upper limb. He is haemodynamically stable, afebrile, and his blood results from this morning are unremarkable. The treating team are concerned that the patient has had a cerebral vasospasm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV nimodipine","Electroencephalogram (EEG)","MR brain angiography","CT brain angiography and perfusion series","IV tissue plasminogen activator (tPA)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with neurological deterioration in the days following aneurysmal subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH). Differentials include complications of the haemorrhage, such as vasospasm (subsequently causing delayed cerebral ischaemia), hydrocephalus, re-bleeding, and seizure, as well as intercurrent problems such as sepsis, metabolic encephalopathy, and de novo ischaemic stroke. The non-localising features seen (confusion, reduced conscious level, headache) are common across these differentials, but the localising features (left-sided faciobrachial weakness) increase suspicion of a vascular event. Furthermore, this patient is within the peak \u2018vasospasm window\u2019: vasospasm most often presents in the 3 - 10 days post SAH, though it can occur at any stage within 21 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVasospasm is a angiographic phenomenon, which may be asymptomatic. However, vasospasm may impair perfusion, resulting in \u0027delayed cerebral ischaemia\u0027, defined as persistent neurological symptoms for \u0026gt;1 hour. Persistent cerebral ischaemia can result in an ischaemic stroke. Although possible, is unlikely, that this patient\u0027s symptoms would be due to a de novo ischaemic stroke in the peak vasospasm window.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT workup with non-contrast and angiography studies plus perfusion maps\u003C/strong\u003E is the ideal modality in common use to quickly identify or rule out several of these diagnoses, including haemodynamically significant vasospasm which is most likely in this case and certainly requires exclusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMR angiography\u003C/strong\u003E, though used in some centres, is a more expensive and time-consuming study that adds little above a CT perfusion series in this setting. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEEG\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful for identifying epileptic activity if no alternative aetiology is suggested on neuroimaging, and there is suspicion of status epilepticus. Vasospasms can result in seizures, and given the time frame post-surgery and clinical picture, should be ruled out first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV nimodipine \u003C/strong\u003Eis a dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker, which works by inducing vascular smooth muscle relaxation, and is commonly used to manage vasospasm following a subarachnoid haemorrhage. However, in this instance, vasospasm (and complications such as DCI) should be confirmed with imaging before treatment is initiated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003EtPA \u003C/strong\u003Eis indicated for ischaemic stroke secondary to a thrombus / embolus, however not one secondary to vasospasm. Regardless, tPA is contraindicated due to the patient\u0027s recent history of SAH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt should be noted that some cases with a high degree of clinical suspicion, some centres proceed directly to formal cerebral angiography as this more invasive technique remains the gold standard for diagnosis and affords the opportunity to deliver direct treatment (e.g. intra-arterial verapamil) if vasospasm is identified.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT workup with plain brain, CT angiogram, and perfusion mapping is the ideal modality to assess acute deterioration after SAH"],"references":["Handbook of Neurosurgery. Greenberg (ed), 9th edition, 2019. Thieme. ISBN 9781684201372.","Ikram et al. Delayed Cerebral Ischemia after Subarachnoid Hemorrhage. J Stroke Cerebrovasc Dis. 2021 Aug 28;30(11):106064."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32495"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"766"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32495"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-28T12:56:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T09:45:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"766"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47773"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not suitable for a medical student","position":2,"